{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Open your web browser and navigate to `git-scm.com`. Click the **Download** button for your specific operating system to download the installer file to your computer.",
      "title": "Download the Git Installer"
    },
    {
      "text": "Locate the downloaded installer in your downloads folder. Double-click the file (on Windows, it is an `.exe` file; on Mac, open the `.dmg` package) to launch the setup guide.",
      "title": "Run the Installer File"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click **Next** through the setup prompts to accept all the recommended default settings. When you reach the final screen of the installer, click **Install** and wait for the progress bar to finish.",
      "title": "Complete the Setup Wizard"
    },
    {
      "text": "Open your command line interface. On Windows, search for **Command Prompt** or **Git Bash** in the Start menu. On macOS, open the **Terminal** app from your Applications utility folder.",
      "title": "Open Your Command Line"
    },
    {
      "text": "Type `git --version` and press Enter. If the installation was successful, you will see the active version number output, such as `git version 2.42.0`. You are now ready to use Git!",
      "title": "Verify Git is Working"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Park on a flat, level surface. Engage the parking brake fully to prevent the car from rolling. Turn on your hazard lights. Put wheel chocks or heavy rocks behind the tires on the opposite end of the car to ensure total stability.",
      "title": "Secure the Vehicle"
    },
    {
      "text": "Use your lug wrench to loosen each lug nut on the flat tire by turning counterclockwise. **Do not remove them yet**—just break the resistance so they turn easily. You should feel them loosen about one full turn.",
      "title": "Loosen the Lug Nuts"
    },
    {
      "text": "Locate your vehicle's designated jack point under the metal frame near the flat tire. Place the jack securely under this spot, ensuring it contacts the reinforced metal frame, not the plastic trim.",
      "title": "Position the Jack"
    },
    {
      "text": "Crank the jack slowly clockwise to raise the car. Stop when the flat tire is about 6 inches off the ground. **Never put your body under the vehicle** while it is raised. Ensure the jack remains completely stable and vertical.",
      "title": "Raise the Vehicle"
    },
    {
      "text": "Use the wrench or your fingers to completely unscrew and remove all the loosened lug nuts. Keep them safe by placing them together inside your turned-over hubcap or a secure pocket so they do not roll away.",
      "title": "Remove the Lug Nuts Completely"
    },
    {
      "text": "Grip the flat tire by the outer edges and pull it straight toward you off the wheel bolts. If it is stuck, firmly tap the rubber outer edge with your hands to break it free. Set the flat tire down flat on the ground nearby.",
      "title": "Pull Off the Flat Tire"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Set up your French press, a kettle, a timer, and fresh coffee grounds. Ensure your French press is clean and completely dry before starting.",
      "title": "Gather Your Equipment"
    },
    {
      "text": "Boil water in your kettle, then let it sit for 1 minute to cool slightly to about **200°F (93°C)**. Using boiling water can scorch the coffee.",
      "title": "Heat the Water"
    },
    {
      "text": "Add **30 grams** (about 3 tablespoons) of coarsely ground coffee to the bottom of your French press. The grind should look like coarse sea salt.",
      "title": "Measure Coffee Grounds"
    },
    {
      "text": "Start your timer and pour just enough hot water over the grounds to wet them completely (about **60 grams** or 1/4 cup). Watch the coffee puff up and bubble.",
      "title": "Start the Bloom"
    },
    {
      "text": "Let the wet coffee sit for **30 seconds**. This \"bloom\" phase releases trapped carbon dioxide gas and prepares the coffee for extraction.",
      "title": "Wait 30 Seconds"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pour the remaining hot water (about **390 grams** or 1.75 cups) slowly over the grounds, filling the French press near the top.",
      "title": "Pour the Remaining Water"
    },
    {
      "text": "Use a wooden or plastic spoon to gently stir the mixture once or twice. This ensures all grounds are fully submerged and evenly saturated.",
      "title": "Stir Gently"
    },
    {
      "text": "Place the lid on the French press with the plunger pulled all the way up. Do not plunge yet. Let the coffee steep for **4 minutes**.",
      "title": "Place Lid and Steep"
    },
    {
      "text": "Press the plunger down slowly and with steady, gentle pressure. If you feel resistance, pull up slightly and resume pressing down.",
      "title": "Plunge Slowly"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pour the brewed coffee immediately into your mug or a separate carafe. Do not leave leftover coffee in the press, or it will become bitter.",
      "title": "Pour and Serve"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Remove all weeds, grass, rocks, and old plant debris from your chosen planting area. The surface should be completely bare soil before you begin digging.",
      "title": "Clear the Garden Bed"
    },
    {
      "text": "Squeeze a handful of soil. It should form a ball that crumbles easily when poked. If it is muddy, wait for it to dry; if it is dusty, water it lightly and wait 24 hours.",
      "title": "Test the Soil Moisture"
    },
    {
      "text": "Insert a garden fork or shovel 8 to 12 inches deep into the soil. Pry upward to lift and loosen the dirt. Repeat across the entire bed to break up compacted layers.",
      "title": "Loosen the Soil"
    },
    {
      "text": "Add a 2- to 3-inch layer of well-rotted organic compost over the entire surface of the bed. You should see a dark, rich layer completely covering the lighter garden soil underneath.",
      "title": "Spread Organic Compost"
    },
    {
      "text": "Scatter a slow-release organic tomato fertilizer or **bone meal** evenly over the compost layer according to package directions. Tomatoes need this initial phosphorus boost for strong root growth.",
      "title": "Sprinkle Fertilizer or Bone Meal"
    },
    {
      "text": "Use your garden fork or hand tiller to blend the compost and fertilizer into the top 6 to 8 inches of soil. The surface mixture should look uniform and feel crumbly.",
      "title": "Mix the Amendments In"
    },
    {
      "text": "Use a garden rake to smooth out the surface of the soil, breaking up any remaining large clods. The bed should look flat, even, and be slightly raised above the surrounding pathways.",
      "title": "Rake and Level the Bed"
    },
    {
      "text": "Spray the bed lightly with a garden hose set to a gentle shower mode. The soil should be damp but not muddy, leaving it settled and ready for your tomato seedlings.",
      "title": "Settle with a Light Watering"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Iron your fabric on a flat surface to remove all wrinkles. Any folds or creases will cause your measurements and cuts to be uneven.",
      "title": "Press Your Fabric"
    },
    {
      "text": "Fold the fabric in half, aligning the selvages (the self-finished flat edges). Smooth out any bubbles or shifts. The fabric should lie perfectly flat on your cutting mat.",
      "title": "Fold and Align the Fabric"
    },
    {
      "text": "Lay your paper pattern pieces on top of the folded fabric. Position the main body piece and the cuff piece according to the pattern layout diagram, matching any \"place on fold\" lines.",
      "title": "Place the Pattern Pieces"
    },
    {
      "text": "Insert straight pins through the pattern paper and both layers of fabric. Place pins every 4 to 6 inches along the edges, pointing them inward so they do not block your scissors.",
      "title": "Pin the Pattern to Fabric"
    },
    {
      "text": "Use a ruler to measure the distance from the printed grainline arrow on the pattern to the fabric's selvage edge. Make sure this distance is identical at both ends of the arrow.",
      "title": "Measure the Grainline"
    },
    {
      "text": "Use sharp fabric shears to cut along the outer solid lines of the pattern. Keep the bottom blade of your shears flat against the table for the straightest, cleanest cuts.",
      "title": "Cut Along the Pattern Lines"
    },
    {
      "text": "Carefully pull out all the pins and set them in a pincushion. Lift the paper pattern pieces off to reveal your freshly cut pillowcase panels.",
      "title": "Remove the Pins"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Clip your digital tuner onto the headstock of your guitar, or open your tuning app on your phone. Position it so you can clearly see the screen while sitting comfortably with your guitar.",
      "title": "Turn on Your Tuner"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the thickest string (6th string). Look at the tuner. If it shows **E** and the needle is in the center, you are in tune. If it's flat (left), turn the peg away from you to tighten it. If it's sharp (right), loosen it first, then tune up to **E**.",
      "title": "Tune the Low E String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the 5th string. Adjust the tuning peg until the tuner displays **A** with the needle perfectly centered. Always tune up from a lower pitch to prevent the string from slipping out of tune later.",
      "title": "Tune the A String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the 4th string. Turn the peg to align the needle in the center for the note **D**. If you overshoot and the pitch is too high, loosen the string below **D** and slowly tighten it back up to the note.",
      "title": "Tune the D String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the 3rd string. Watch the tuner and adjust the corresponding peg until the screen displays **G** and lights up green or centers the needle. Ensure you are only turning the peg for the 3rd string.",
      "title": "Tune the G String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the 2nd string. Note that on standard headstocks, the tuning pegs for the thinnest strings may turn in the opposite direction. Adjust the peg until the tuner reads **B** and indicates it is perfectly in tune.",
      "title": "Tune the B String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the thinnest string (1st string). Carefully turn the peg until the tuner displays a high **E** in the center. Pluck gently, as this thin string is under the highest tension and can snap if overtightened.",
      "title": "Tune the High E String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck each string from the 6th to the 1st string one more time. Tuning the other strings changes the overall neck tension, which might make your first few strings slightly flat. Make quick, minor adjustments as needed.",
      "title": "Recheck and Fine-Tune"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Turn your camera's mode dial to **M** (Manual). This gives you full control over all exposure settings. You should see the letter 'M' indicated on your screen or top dial.",
      "title": "Switch to Manual Mode"
    },
    {
      "text": "Press the **ISO** button and use the dial to choose a value. Start with `100` or `200` for bright daylight, or choose a higher number like `800` or `1600` if you are indoors or in low light.",
      "title": "Set Your ISO"
    },
    {
      "text": "Locate your camera's aperture control (often the front dial). Adjust it to set your f-stop. Use a low number like `f/2.8` for a blurry background, or a higher number like `f/8` to keep the scene sharp.",
      "title": "Set Your Aperture"
    },
    {
      "text": "Rotate the main command dial (usually near your thumb) to set the shutter speed. Use at least `1/125` for static subjects, or `1/500` and faster to freeze quick motion.",
      "title": "Set Your Shutter Speed"
    },
    {
      "text": "Look through your viewfinder or at the LCD screen to locate the exposure meter scale (running from `-3` to `+3`). If the indicator bar is to the left (minus), your image is underexposed.",
      "title": "Read the Exposure Meter"
    },
    {
      "text": "Adjust your shutter speed, aperture, or ISO until the indicator mark sits exactly at `0` in the center of the meter. This represents the camera's calculated neutral exposure.",
      "title": "Balance the Meter to Zero"
    },
    {
      "text": "Press the shutter button halfway down to lock focus, then press it fully to take the photo. Review the image on your LCD screen to ensure the highlights and shadows look natural.",
      "title": "Take a Test Photo"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Stand with your feet slightly wider than shoulder-width apart. Point your toes slightly outward, about 5 to 20 degrees. You should feel balanced and firmly planted on the floor.",
      "title": "Set Your Foot Stance"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pull your shoulders back, lift your chest, and look straight ahead. Brace your core muscles as if you are about to receive a light punch. This keeps your spine neutral and stable.",
      "title": "Align Your Upper Body"
    },
    {
      "text": "Start the movement by pushing your hips back, as if you are sitting down on an invisible chair behind you. Do not bend your knees first. You should feel your weight shift slightly toward your heels.",
      "title": "Initiate the Hinge"
    },
    {
      "text": "Bend your knees and lower your body until your thighs are parallel to the floor. Keep your heels glued to the ground and your torso upright. You should feel your thigh and glute muscles working hard to hold this position.",
      "title": "Lower into the Squat"
    },
    {
      "text": "Look down quickly to verify your knees are pointing in the same direction as your toes. Do not let your knees collapse inward. If they are bowing in, actively push them outward.",
      "title": "Check Knee Alignment"
    },
    {
      "text": "Push hard through your heels to return to the starting position. Keep your chest up throughout the rise. Squeeze your glutes at the top of the movement to complete one perfect rep.",
      "title": "Drive Up to Stand"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Reúna 500g de farinha de trigo, 10g de fermento biológico seco, 300ml de água morna, 10g de sal e 5g de açúcar. Certifique-se de que a água está morna ao toque (cerca de 38°C) e não quente para não matar o fermento.",
      "title": "Separe os ingredientes"
    },
    {
      "text": "Em uma tigela pequena, misture a água morna, o açúcar e o fermento biológico. Deixe descansar por 5 a 10 minutos. **Você verá uma espuma espessa se formar na superfície**, confirmando que o fermento está ativo.",
      "title": "Ative o fermento"
    },
    {
      "text": "Em uma tigela grande, adicione a farinha de trigo e o sal. Misture bem com uma colher para garantir que o sal fique distribuído de maneira uniforme pela farinha.",
      "title": "Misture os ingredientes secos"
    },
    {
      "text": "Abra um buraco no centro da farinha e despeje a mistura de fermento ativado. Use as mãos ou uma colher resistente para incorporar a farinha das laterais para o centro até que toda a água seja absorvida.",
      "title": "Junte os líquidos aos secos"
    },
    {
      "text": "Limpe uma superfície lisa e espalhe uma leve camada de farinha sobre ela. Transfira a massa úmida da tigela diretamente para essa bancada.",
      "title": "Prepare a bancada de trabalho"
    },
    {
      "text": "Use a palma da mão para empurrar a massa para a frente e depois dobre-a de volta sobre si mesma. Gire a massa 90 graus e repita o movimento continuamente por 10 minutos até que ela fique macia e lisa.",
      "title": "Sove a massa"
    },
    {
      "text": "Retire um pedaço pequeno de massa e estique-o com os dedos de dentro para fora. **A massa deve se abrir até ficar fina e translúcida sem rasgar**. Se rasgar de imediato, sove por mais 2 minutos.",
      "title": "Faça o teste do ponto de véu"
    },
    {
      "text": "Modele a massa em formato de bola lisa. Coloque-a em uma tigela levemente untada com óleo, cubra com um pano úmido e deixe descansar em um local morno até que dobre de volume.",
      "title": "Forme uma bola para o descanso"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Busca las **llaves de paso** debajo del lavabo y gíralas hacia la derecha (sentido de las agujas del reloj) hasta que se detengan. Abre el grifo para confirmar que ya no sale agua.",
      "title": "Cierra la llave de paso"
    },
    {
      "text": "Coloca un tapón o un trapo limpio en el drenaje del lavabo. Esto evitará que los tornillos o piezas pequeñas caigan accidentalmente por la tubería durante la reparación.",
      "title": "Bloquea el desagüe"
    },
    {
      "text": "Usa un destornillador plano y delgado para hacer palanca suavemente debajo de la tapa de plástico de la manija (la que indica frío o caliente) hasta retirarla.",
      "title": "Retira la tapa decorativa"
    },
    {
      "text": "Usa un destornillador Phillips o una llave Allen para aflojar y retirar el tornillo que se encuentra debajo de la tapa decorativa. Guarda el tornillo en un lugar seguro.",
      "title": "Quita el tornillo de la manija"
    },
    {
      "text": "Jala la manija firmemente hacia arriba para sacarla del vástago. Si se siente atascada, muévela suavemente de lado a lado hasta que se desprenda por completo.",
      "title": "Retira la manija del grifo"
    },
    {
      "text": "Usa una llave inglesa ajustable para girar la tuerca de retención hacia la izquierda (sentido contrario a las agujas del reloj) hasta aflojarla y retirarla por completo.",
      "title": "Desenrosca la tuerca de retención"
    },
    {
      "text": "Jala el cartucho o vástago viejo hacia arriba para extraerlo. Reemplázalo por una pieza nueva idéntica, o cambia los empaques de goma (**arandelas**) desgastados que causan la gotera.",
      "title": "Reemplaza el cartucho o los empaques"
    },
    {
      "text": "Introduce el cartucho nuevo, enrosca la tuerca de retención con la llave inglesa, vuelve a colocar la manija, aprieta el tornillo y presiona la tapa decorativa en su lugar.",
      "title": "Reensambla el grifo"
    },
    {
      "text": "Gira las llaves de paso debajo del lavabo hacia la izquierda para abrir el agua. Abre el grifo para purgar el aire de la tubería y ciérralo para confirmar que la gotera ha desaparecido.",
      "title": "Abre el agua y verifica la reparación"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Click on the **File** menu in the top-left corner of your screen. A drop-down menu with several options will appear.",
      "title": "Open the File Menu"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click **Save As** from the menu list. This opens the dialog box that allows you to name your file and select its storage location.",
      "title": "Select Save As"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click **Browse** or select **This PC**, then choose a folder like **Documents** or **Desktop** where you want to keep your file.",
      "title": "Choose Your Storage Location"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click inside the **File name** text box. Type a clear, recognizable name for your document, such as `Project_Draft_V1`.",
      "title": "Name Your Document"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click the **Save as type** drop-down menu. Ensure it is set to the standard document format, like **Word Document (*.docx)**.",
      "title": "Select the File Format"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click the **Save** button in the bottom-right corner of the window. The dialog window will close automatically.",
      "title": "Click the Save Button"
    },
    {
      "text": "Look at the top center of your application window. You should see your new file name `Project_Draft_V1` displayed in the title bar.",
      "title": "Verify Your Document Is Saved"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Place your motherboard box on a flat, clean table to use as a non-conductive workspace. Touch a metal object or wear an anti-static wrist strap to discharge static electricity before handling any computer parts.",
      "title": "Prepare Your Workspace"
    },
    {
      "text": "Gently lift the metal tension arm on the motherboard's CPU socket. Align the golden triangle on the corner of your CPU with the triangle on the socket corner, lower the CPU gently without force, and lower the tension arm back down to lock it.",
      "title": "Install the CPU"
    },
    {
      "text": "Push open the retention clips on your motherboard's RAM slots (usually slots 2 and 4). Align the notch on the bottom of the RAM stick with the break in the slot, and push down firmly on both ends until you hear a click.",
      "title": "Install the RAM Modules"
    },
    {
      "text": "Locate the M.2 slot near the CPU. Insert your M.2 SSD into the slot at a 30-degree angle, press the card flat against the motherboard standoff, and secure it with the small M.2 screw or tool-free latch.",
      "title": "Install the M.2 SSD"
    },
    {
      "text": "Apply a pea-sized drop of thermal paste to the center of the CPU. Place the cooler bracket over the CPU socket and secure the screws in a diagonal cross-pattern to ensure even pressure. Connect the fan power cable to the motherboard's `CPU_FAN` header.",
      "title": "Mount the CPU Cooler"
    },
    {
      "text": "Lay your PC case flat on its side. Push the motherboard I/O shield firmly into the rear cutout of the case until it clicks (skip if it is pre-installed on your motherboard). Ensure the brass motherboard standoffs align with your motherboard's mounting holes.",
      "title": "Prepare the PC Case"
    },
    {
      "text": "Carefully lower the motherboard into the case, aligning its ports with the rear I/O shield. Secure the board to the case standoffs using the screws provided in your case accessory box. Tighten them firmly, but do not overtighten.",
      "title": "Mount the Motherboard"
    },
    {
      "text": "Slide the Power Supply Unit (PSU) into the bottom-rear chamber of the case with the fan facing downwards toward the ventilation grill. Secure the unit from the outside back of the case using four PSU screws.",
      "title": "Install the Power Supply"
    },
    {
      "text": "Route and plug the large 24-pin ATX power cable into the right side of the motherboard. Next, plug the 8-pin (or 4+4 pin) CPU power cable into the top-left connector labeled `CPU_PWR1`. Push until you hear a physical click.",
      "title": "Connect Power Cables"
    },
    {
      "text": "Remove the expansion slot covers on the back of the case that align with your top PCIe x16 slot. Push open the PCIe slot latch, insert the GPU firmly until the latch clicks, secure its bracket to the case with screws, and plug in the PCIe power cables.",
      "title": "Install the GPU"
    },
    {
      "text": "Locate the thin front panel cables (`POWER SW`, `RESET SW`, `HDD LED`). Plug them into the `JFP1` header on the bottom right of the motherboard, matching the positive (+) and negative (-) pins as shown in your motherboard manual.",
      "title": "Connect Front Panel Headers"
    },
    {
      "text": "Connect your monitor directly to the GPU ports (not the motherboard), plug in the main power cable, and flip the PSU switch to the \"I\" position. Press the case power button. Your CPU fan should spin and a BIOS screen should appear on your monitor.",
      "title": "Plug In and Power On"
    }
  ]
}
